'use strict';

const GLOSSARY = [
['A/B test','', 'A controlled comparison between two versions to estimate the effect of one change.','Compare two signup messages for similar visitors.','Changing several elements and attributing the result to one.'],
['Activation','', 'The moment a user first completes a behavior that represents meaningful value.','A team imports data and completes its first weekly review.','Using account creation as a universal proxy for value.'],
['Add-on','', 'An optional capability or service purchased separately from the main offer.','An advanced audit module for regulated accounts.','Removing an essential capability from the core offer.'],
['Admin','', 'A user with permission to configure an account, access, policies, or integrations.','An admin defines invitation rules for a team.','Assuming admins represent the daily end-user experience.'],
['Adoption','', 'The beginning of use among people or accounts eligible for a capability.','Thirty percent of exposed team accounts use bulk import.','Dividing by all users, including people who cannot use it.'],
['Application Programming Interface','API', 'A defined contract that lets software systems exchange data or trigger capabilities.','A billing product exposes an API for creating invoices.','Treating an API endpoint as a complete customer outcome.'],
['Annual Recurring Revenue','ARR', 'Recurring revenue normalized to an annual value.','Use ARR to discuss the size of an annual SaaS base.','Mixing services, one-time fees, or unsigned pipeline into ARR.'],
['Artificial intelligence','AI', 'Software techniques that perform tasks associated with prediction, generation, classification, or reasoning.','An AI system drafts a summary that a manager reviews.','Adding AI without defining the job, reliability threshold, or human control.'],
['Assumption','', 'A belief treated as true even though it has not yet been established by evidence.','Assume admins can invite coworkers without approval.','Hiding an assumption inside a confident recommendation.'],
['Average Revenue per Account','ARPA', 'Average recurring revenue generated by an account during a defined period.','Compare ARPA before and after a packaging change.','Letting a few very large accounts hide the typical customer economics.'],
['Awareness','', 'A person’s knowledge that a product or capability exists and may be relevant.','Eligible users see import at the moment they need to migrate data.','Explaining every adoption problem as a promotion problem.'],
['B2B','Business to Business', 'A model in which one business sells to another business.','A billing platform sells to accounting firms.','Assuming buyer, user, and budget owner are the same person.'],
['Backlog','', 'A prioritizable inventory of possible work, opportunities, defects, and debt.','Maintain candidate problems without promising all of them.','Treating the backlog as product strategy.'],
['Baseline','', 'The reference level against which later change is compared.','Measure activation before changing onboarding.','Comparing against a period with different seasonality or population.'],
['Beachhead','', 'A deliberately narrow starting segment used to establish traction before expansion.','Start with agencies that bill by the hour before broader professional services.','Choosing a small group without intense pain or expansion potential.'],
['Beta','', 'A real product version released to a controlled audience for learning and stabilization.','Ten design partners use the new report.','Using customers as unpaid QA without clear expectations.'],
['Business impact','', 'The effect of a problem or decision on revenue, cost, risk, or a business objective.','Reduce failed payments that create involuntary churn.','Calling something impactful without naming the mechanism.'],
['Buyer','', 'The person who runs or strongly influences the purchasing process.','An operations director evaluates vendors and contract terms.','Assuming the buyer performs the daily work.'],
['Buyer persona','', 'A behavioral description of the person involved in purchase evaluation.','A finance leader who needs a defensible payback case.','Filling it with demographics that do not affect buying.'],
['CAC','Customer Acquisition Cost', 'The Sales and marketing cost attributed to acquiring customers.','Compare acquisition efficiency across channels.','Ignoring Sales labor, attribution windows, or contribution margin.'],
['Chief Financial Officer','CFO', 'The executive accountable for financial strategy, reporting, capital, and financial risk.','A CFO approves an annual software commitment.','Assuming the CFO is the daily user because they own the budget.'],
['Chief Operating Officer','COO', 'The executive accountable for how the organization operates and executes its strategy.','A COO sponsors a workflow standardization program.','Treating executive sponsorship as evidence that end users can adopt the workflow.'],
['Champion','', 'An internal advocate who helps a solution gain support and adoption.','A team lead coordinates the pilot and persuades peers.','Confusing enthusiasm with authority or budget.'],
['Churn','', 'The loss of customers or recurring revenue during a defined period.','Measure monthly logo churn for paid accounts.','Mixing customer churn and revenue churn.'],
['Cohort','', 'A group sharing a start event or period so its behavior can be compared over time.','Compare teams activated in January with teams activated in February.','Comparing cohorts before they have equal time to mature.'],
['Commitment','', 'An explicit promise or obligation the organization has decided to honor.','Complete a regulatory migration before the communicated deadline.','Calling every roadmap intention a commitment.'],
['Concierge test','', 'A transparent manual delivery of value used to test demand or workflow.','An analyst manually prepares the weekly profitability report.','Scaling the manual service without defining what must be learned.'],
['Confidence','', 'The strength of evidence supporting an estimate, interpretation, or hypothesis.','Confidence rises when usage, interviews, and a test converge.','Scoring political conviction rather than evidence quality.'],
['Conversion','', 'The proportion moving from one explicitly defined stage to another.','Measure activated trials that become paid accounts.','Omitting the denominator, window, or transition.'],
['Core product','', 'The capabilities and experiences that sustain the product’s central value proposition.','Recording, reviewing, and billing work form the core of a profitability tool.','Calling everything already built “core” to prevent removal.'],
['Cost of delay','', 'The value lost or risk accumulated for each unit of time an initiative waits.','Fraud exposure increases every week without a control.','Confusing waiting cost with build effort.'],
['Customer','', 'The account or party with which the company has a commercial relationship.','The agency is the customer while consultants are users.','Using the word as if every role agrees.'],
['Customer advisory board','CAB', 'A recurring group of customers who provide structured advice to the company.','Discuss governance needs with selected customers each quarter.','Treating members as a representative sample of the market.'],
['Customer journey','', 'The sequence of contexts and interactions through which a customer pursues an objective.','Map the path from discovery through renewal.','Drawing the ideal company process instead of observed behavior.'],
['Customer Relationship Management','CRM', 'A system used to manage commercial accounts, interactions, opportunities, and relationship history.','Sales records why an opportunity was lost in the CRM.','Treating a required CRM field as verified customer evidence.'],
['Customer lifetime value','LTV', 'An estimate of the economic value generated across a customer relationship.','Use LTV to bound sustainable acquisition investment.','Using false precision when churn and margin are unstable.'],
['Customer Success','CS', 'The function that helps customers achieve outcomes and continue the relationship.','CS identifies adoption barriers inside established accounts.','Turning every customer comment into a product priority.'],
['Comma-Separated Values','CSV', 'A plain-text tabular data format in which fields are separated by commas or a similar delimiter.','An admin imports team members from a CSV file.','Assuming every exported CSV has the same columns, encoding, or delimiter.'],
['Decision owner','', 'The person accountable for driving and closing a decision after relevant input.','A PM owns the prioritization recommendation.','Using ownership as permission to ignore specialists.'],
['Decision rule','', 'A condition agreed in advance that connects a result to an action.','Scale if activation rises without crossing the Support guardrail.','Inventing the rule after seeing the data.'],
['Delivery','', 'The work of turning a product decision into reliable, usable software.','Build, test, release, and stabilize an integration.','Equating shipment speed with value creation.'],
['Delivery Manager','', 'A professional who improves delivery flow, coordination, and impediment removal.','Expose dependencies across teams during a migration.','Measuring success only by output velocity.'],
['Dependency','', 'A condition outside the immediate work that is required for progress or success.','New billing depends on completing a data migration.','Discovering it only near launch.'],
['Design','', 'The discipline of understanding and shaping how people experience and use a solution.','Test a workflow with users before full implementation.','Reducing Design to visual polish at the end.'],
['Design partner','', 'A customer who collaborates closely in discovery and validation.','Two agencies help shape a margin-review workflow.','Building custom work without learning goals or boundaries.'],
['Detractor','', 'A person who actively resists adoption because of incentives, risk, or experience.','A manager blocks a rollout that reduces approval control.','Labeling every disagreement as irrational resistance.'],
['Discovery','', 'Work that reduces uncertainty about the problem, solution, customer, and business.','Combine interviews, usage data, and a prototype.','Treating it as a phase that excludes Engineering.'],
['Economic buyer','', 'The person with final authority over the budget.','A CFO approves the annual contract.','Confusing influence with purchasing authority.'],
['End user','', 'The person who directly operates the product to perform work.','An analyst uses software purchased by a finance director.','Confusing the user with the chooser or payer.'],
['Engagement','', 'The frequency or depth of meaningful product use.','Managers review active projects each week.','Counting clicks that have no relationship with value.'],
['Engineering','', 'The discipline responsible for technical feasibility, construction, and operation.','Engineering tests latency before a real-time promise.','Involving engineers only after solution and date are fixed.'],
['Enterprise','', 'A large-organization context with complex purchasing, governance, and multiple stakeholders.','An account requires SSO, audit logs, and Security approval.','Using enterprise merely to mean a high-paying customer.'],
['Epic','', 'An operational grouping of related stories or tasks.','Group work for importing organization members.','Using an epic as strategic justification.'],
['Expansion revenue','', 'Additional revenue from existing customers through seats, usage, or upgrades.','A team adds seats after adopting collaboration.','Celebrating expansion without considering contraction.'],
['Experiment','', 'A planned intervention intended to test a hypothesis and inform a decision.','Release alternative onboarding to a comparable group.','Calling every launch an experiment.'],
['Exposure','', 'The condition of actually receiving or seeing a change.','A user has the flag enabled and opens the relevant screen.','Measuring adoption among people never exposed.'],
['Fake door','', 'A visible entry point used to measure interest before the capability exists.','A button explains that a beta is not yet available.','Deceiving or charging people for a nonexistent feature.'],
['Feasibility risk','', 'The risk that a solution cannot be built, scaled, secured, or operated adequately.','Latency makes real-time summarization impractical.','Evaluating feasibility only after making a promise.'],
['Feature','', 'A specific capability offered by a product.','A configurable data export.','Describing the absence of a feature as the customer problem.'],
['Feature flag','', 'A control that enables a change for selected audiences without a new deployment.','Release a workflow to five percent of accounts.','Leaving old flags without an owner or removal date.'],
['Feature request','', 'A request expressed as a desired capability or solution.','A customer asks for a daily email export.','Treating it as a ready specification.'],
['Fit','', 'The degree of alignment between audience, problem, offer, and product capabilities.','Hourly agencies fit a profitability workflow better than casual freelancers.','Treating fit as a feeling without behavioral or economic evidence.'],
['Founder','', 'A person who started the company and often spans product, business, and operations.','A founder sees a repeated problem while serving early customers.','Treating intuition as proof or dismissing it because it is informal.'],
['Framework','', 'A reusable structure of questions, criteria, or steps for organizing reasoning.','Use the seven questions to frame a decision.','Applying the structure mechanically as if it were the answer.'],
['Freemium','', 'A model with a persistent free plan and paid limits or capabilities.','Individual use is free while team collaboration is paid.','Confusing freemium with a temporary trial.'],
['Funnel','', 'A measured sequence of stages toward an outcome.','Visit, signup, activation, and payment.','Assuming every user follows one linear path.'],
['Go-to-market','GTM', 'The coordinated system for bringing an offer to market and creating adoption or revenue.','Product, Marketing, and Sales coordinate a launch.','Reducing GTM to an announcement campaign.'],
['Guardrail metric','', 'A measure that protects against unacceptable harm while another metric is optimized.','Critical Support tickets must not increase during onboarding simplification.','Ignoring the guardrail when the primary metric wins.'],
['Hypothesis','', 'A falsifiable statement connecting an intervention, audience, mechanism, and expected outcome.','CSV import will improve activation because it removes manual setup.','Writing an expected result without a mechanism.'],
['Ideal Customer Profile','ICP', 'A description of the type of organization most likely to gain value and create a healthy business relationship.','Agencies with 20–100 people that bill by the hour.','Describing the entire existing customer base.'],
['Initiative','', 'A coherent bet or set of efforts oriented toward an outcome.','Reduce time to value for new teams.','Using the word as a more impressive name for a project.'],
['Instrumentation','', 'Events and properties implemented to make behavior observable.','Record exposure, import completion, and errors.','Adding measurement only after launch.'],
['Jobs to be Done','JTBD', 'A perspective focused on the progress a person seeks in a particular context.','Close project margin before the weekly meeting.','Turning the job into a generic aspiration.'],
['Kill criteria','', 'A pre-agreed condition for stopping a bet or experiment.','Stop after two iterations without meaningful activation.','Moving the threshold to protect sunk cost.'],
['Lagging indicator','', 'A measure that confirms an outcome after the necessary time has passed.','Ninety-day account retention.','Waiting for it without any earlier signals.'],
['Leading indicator','', 'An early signal with a plausible relationship to a later outcome.','Complete the first workflow on day one.','Treating correlation as causal proof.'],
['Limited rollout','', 'A release restricted by audience, region, or percentage to control risk and learn.','Enable the change one region at a time.','Generalizing from a biased early group.'],
['Minimum detectable effect','MDE', 'The smallest change a test can reliably detect or that is worth acting on.','Define an activation improvement large enough to justify rollout.','Choosing it after results are visible.'],
['Minimum viable product','MVP', 'The smallest product that delivers real value and tests a thesis in use.','A complete simple workflow for one segment.','Shipping something broken, valueless, or merely small.'],
['Monthly Recurring Revenue','MRR', 'Recurring revenue normalized to a monthly value.','Monitor the base of monthly subscriptions.','Mixing bookings or one-time revenue into MRR.'],
['Net Promoter Score','NPS', 'A standardized measure of stated willingness to recommend.','Track perception and investigate the reasons behind scores.','Using NPS alone as proof of loyalty.'],
['Net Revenue Retention','NRR', 'Revenue retained from the existing base after expansion, contraction, and churn.','Evaluate growth inside current customers.','Including revenue from newly acquired customers.'],
['North Star Metric','NSM', 'A central measure of customer value intended to align several teams.','Useful workflows completed by active teams.','Choosing revenue without a value mechanism.'],
['Opportunity','', 'A customer problem or need that could create value if addressed.','Reduce rework in weekly billing.','Writing it as a predetermined solution.'],
['Opportunity cost','', 'The value of the best alternative abandoned when a choice is made.','Delay activation work to build a custom report.','Treating product capacity as free.'],
['Outcome','', 'An observable change in behavior or results.','More accounts reach first value.','Writing a delivered artifact as the outcome.'],
['Output','', 'An artifact or unit of work produced by the team.','A new onboarding flow is released.','Declaring output as proof of impact.'],
['Packaging','', 'The grouping of capabilities, limits, and services into understandable offers or plans.','Advanced permissions belong to the team plan.','Confusing packaging with price alone.'],
['Pattern validation','', 'Confirmation that a similar problem recurs across independent relevant cases.','The same job appears in four ICP accounts.','Counting repeated reports from one account as separate patterns.'],
['Payback period','', 'The time required for contribution margin to repay acquisition cost.','A channel repays CAC in fourteen months.','Calculating with revenue instead of margin.'],
['Paywall','', 'A barrier requiring payment or a plan change to access a capability.','Advanced exports require a paid plan.','Adding a paywall before understanding where value appears.'],
['Persona','', 'A behavioral archetype of a person in a specific work context.','An operations manager closes margin every Friday.','Prioritizing age and hobbies unrelated to behavior.'],
['Pilot','', 'A controlled implementation with a defined audience, duration, and purpose.','Test an integration with three accounts for six weeks.','Allowing the pilot to become permanent without review.'],
['Pipeline','', 'Commercial opportunities tracked across stages of a sales process.','Sales tracks discovery, technical evaluation, and negotiation.','Counting the entire pipeline as contracted revenue.'],
['PLG','Product-led growth', 'A growth model in which the product experience drives acquisition, activation, or expansion.','A self-service trial creates paid teams.','Assuming PLG means Sales never participates.'],
['Post-launch review','', 'A structured review of hypothesis, results, risks, and learning after release.','Decide whether to scale after the cohort matures.','Turning the review into an output celebration.'],
['Power user','', 'A frequent, advanced user who explores capabilities beyond the common path.','An analyst creates automations used by the team.','Designing the main experience only for experts.'],
['Premortem','', 'An exercise that imagines a future failure and works backward to plausible causes.','Assume the launch caused confusion and identify preventive signals.','Producing generic fear without actions or monitoring.'],
['Pricing','', 'The process of defining price, charging unit, tiers, and commercial rules.','Charge by seat, processed volume, or both.','Setting price only by adding a desired margin to cost.'],
['Quality Assurance','QA', 'The practices used to prevent, detect, and understand defects and quality risks.','QA verifies a billing change across currencies and permissions.','Treating quality as a final testing phase owned by one person.'],
['Product','', 'The discipline and organizational perspective connecting customer problems, business strategy, and product evolution.','Product organizes the decision while Design and Engineering deepen the response.','Using Product as a synonym for the Product Manager.'],
['Product analytics','', 'The use of behavioral data to understand product use and outcomes.','Analyze an activation funnel and retention cohorts.','Instrumenting events without a decision question.'],
['Product debt','', 'Accumulated product decisions that reduce coherence and future adaptability.','Customer-specific permission exceptions.','Treating it as technical debt only.'],
['Product Management','PM', 'The discipline of choosing relevant problems and coordinating learning, strategy, and delivery to produce outcomes.','Prioritize time to value over another isolated feature.','Confusing it with project management or backlog administration.'],
['Product Manager','PM', 'A professional who improves the quality of product decisions with the team.','Connect recurring pain to business impact and the smallest useful test.','Treating the PM as Engineering’s boss or sole idea owner.'],
['Product risk','', 'Uncertainty that can prevent value or create harm.','Value, usability, feasibility, and viability risks.','Listing risks without identifying the critical one.'],
['Product strategy','', 'A coherent set of choices about where to play and how to win.','Focus on hourly agencies acquired through a product-led motion.','Calling a project list a strategy.'],
['Product thinking','', 'Structured reasoning about problems, audiences, evidence, impact, risk, and decisions.','Question whether a request represents a pattern before roadmap inclusion.','Reducing it to mechanical framework use.'],
['Product-led sales','PLS', 'The use of product behavior to guide commercial engagement.','Sales contacts an account with rapid seat expansion.','Treating every inbound lead as product-led sales.'],
['Product-market fit','PMF', 'A condition in which a defined market repeatedly obtains enough value to sustain demand.','Cohorts retain while acquisition continues to find response.','Reducing PMF to one survey or universal threshold.'],
['Progressive disclosure','', 'A design principle that reveals complexity gradually as it becomes relevant.','Show advanced settings after custom mode is enabled.','Hiding essential capabilities in the name of simplicity.'],
['Project Manager','', 'A professional who coordinates scope, schedule, dependencies, and communication for a defined project.','Coordinate a migration across teams and milestones.','Confusing execution management with product-problem selection.'],
['Proof of concept','PoC', 'A limited implementation used to reduce a technical uncertainty.','Validate processing latency with realistic data.','Shipping the proof of concept as an end-user product.'],
['Prospect','', 'A person or organization that could become a customer and is being evaluated commercially.','A company in trial reviews security requirements.','Treating prospect opinion as equivalent to observed use.'],
['Prototype','', 'A representation built to learn about a solution or interaction.','Test a clickable permission flow with admins.','Interpreting praise as intent to adopt.'],
['Qualitative evidence','', 'Evidence about motives, context, mechanisms, and meaning.','An interview reveals a weekly workaround.','Inferring prevalence from a few conversations.'],
['Quantitative evidence','', 'Numerical evidence about distribution, frequency, or behavior.','A funnel shows concentrated abandonment.','Assuming correlation explains cause.'],
['RICE','Reach · Impact · Confidence · Effort', 'A prioritization model that compares expected reach and impact, adjusted by confidence and effort.','Use RICE to expose assumptions across comparable opportunities.','Treating a calculated score as an objective strategy decision.'],
['Reach','', 'The number or proportion of people or accounts affected in a defined window.','The issue affects 30% of ICP accounts each quarter.','Using the total market instead of eligible exposure.'],
['Retention','', 'Continued use or continued commercial presence over time.','Accounts remain active after ninety days.','Changing the definition between cohorts.'],
['Revenue at risk','', 'Revenue exposed to loss or non-realization.','ARR attached to renewals blocked by compliance.','Counting uncertain pipeline as guaranteed revenue.'],
['Reversibility','', 'The ease and cost of undoing a decision.','Copy is reversible; a data migration is not.','Demanding the same evidence for every decision.'],
['Roadmap','', 'A communication of direction, sequence, outcomes, and confidence.','Now activation; next collaboration; later governance.','Turning it into a fixed list of features.'],
['Roadmap commitment','', 'A deliberate promise concerning an outcome, scope, or date.','Complete a regulatory migration by the legal deadline.','Treating an intention as a contract.'],
['Rollback','', 'The reversal of a released change.','Disable a new checkout flow through a flag.','Planning it only after an incident occurs.'],
['Rollback criteria','', 'The threshold that requires a released change to be reversed.','Rollback after any critical financial error.','Leaving the threshold subjective during a crisis.'],
['Rollout','', 'The process of releasing a change progressively across an audience.','Design partners, ten percent, fifty percent, everyone.','Confusing availability with adoption.'],
['SaaS','Software as a Service', 'Software delivered as an ongoing service, usually online and commonly billed by subscription or usage.','A financial tool accessed in a browser and billed monthly.','Treating SaaS as a billing model only.'],
['Sales','', 'The function that finds, qualifies, negotiates, and closes commercial opportunities.','Sales records the context behind a purchase objection.','Treating Sales as noise or as an automatic roadmap owner.'],
['Sales-led','', 'A model in which a Sales process drives qualification, evaluation, and closing.','A seller coordinates demo, Security, and contract.','Assuming the product experience no longer matters.'],
['Scope','', 'The explicit boundary of cases and capabilities included in work.','A beta supports CSV but not continuous synchronization.','Reducing scope randomly until value disappears.'],
['Scope reduction','', 'The planned removal of cases or capabilities while preserving the central outcome.','A beta supports one SSO provider.','Cutting quality or the essential value proposition.'],
['Search logs','', 'Records of search terms that reveal intent, vocabulary, and missing results.','Frequent searches for “invoice” reveal navigation friction.','Treating ambiguous words as exact feature requests.'],
['Security','', 'The function and practices that protect systems, data, and access.','Security evaluates authentication and audit controls.','Treating security as late bureaucracy.'],
['Segment','', 'A group defined by attributes useful for analysis or action.','Compare retention between agencies and consultancies.','Creating descriptive groups that change no decision.'],
['Segmentation','', 'The division of an audience into groups useful for comparison or action.','Compare enterprise and self-service behavior.','Creating segments that explain nothing and guide nothing.'],
['Self-service','', 'A model in which customers can evaluate, buy, and use with little human intervention.','A small team begins a trial and subscribes without Sales.','Confusing low human intervention with no support.'],
['Serviceable Available Market','SAM', 'The portion of total demand the offer is capable of serving.','Companies in supported countries with supported integrations.','Assuming access to the entire category.'],
['Serviceable Obtainable Market','SOM', 'The portion of SAM realistically reachable within a defined horizon and capacity.','Agencies the company can acquire over three years.','Presenting ambition as a forecast.'],
['Smoke test','', 'A quick test of an essential signal before deeper validation or construction.','A credible offer page measures whether visitors begin purchase.','Treating initial interest as proof of retention or willingness to pay.'],
['Small and Medium-sized Business','SMB', 'A broad business-size category whose exact employee or revenue limits vary by market and company.','Compare onboarding for SMB accounts with enterprise accounts.','Using SMB as if all smaller companies share one workflow or buying process.'],
['Single Sign-On','SSO', 'An authentication approach that lets a person access multiple systems through one managed identity.','An enterprise customer uses its identity provider to access the product through SSO.','Treating SSO as a cosmetic login option instead of a governance and security capability.'],
['Spike','', 'A short, bounded technical investigation used to reduce uncertainty before commitment.','Test whether search meets the latency requirement.','Allowing the investigation to become an unapproved implementation.'],
['Stakeholder','', 'A person or group that influences or is affected by a decision.','Legal reviews data handling.','Giving every opinion equal decision weight.'],
['Strategic alignment','', 'Consistency with the company’s chosen position, objectives, and capabilities.','Permissions support the enterprise expansion strategy.','Using the phrase as a veto without explaining strategy.'],
['Sunk cost','', 'Past investment that cannot be recovered and should not determine future value.','Months already spent do not justify continuing.','Confusing stopping with wasting the past work.'],
['Support','', 'The function that helps users resolve questions, failures, and blocks.','Support detects an error increase after launch.','Using raw ticket count without growth or severity context.'],
['Support volume','', 'The number of Support contacts within a defined context and period.','Tickets per thousand exposed users.','Using raw counts after the customer base grows.'],
['Target segment','', 'The group deliberately selected for an action, offer, or analysis.','Agency trials with more than twenty users.','Defining it too broadly to learn.'],
['Time to value','TTV', 'The time required for a user to experience a meaningful result.','Hours from signup to the first useful report.','Measuring time to tutorial completion.'],
['Total addressable market','TAM', 'The theoretical total demand for a category under explicit assumptions.','All teams that buy time-tracking software.','Using TAM to justify any opportunity.'],
['Trade-off','', 'A conscious choice between benefits that cannot all be maximized.','Gain speed by limiting rollout reach.','Pretending every objective will improve simultaneously.'],
['Trial','', 'Temporary free access to a paid offer.','Full plan access for fourteen days.','Confusing trial with a permanent free plan.'],
['Usability risk','', 'The risk that people cannot understand or successfully use a solution.','Admins misconfigure permission rules.','Measuring stated satisfaction only.'],
['User','', 'A person who interacts with the product.','A consultant records time.','Assuming the user decides the purchase.'],
['User Experience','UX', 'The complete experience a person has while understanding, using, and living with a product or service.','UX includes setup, error recovery, performance, and Support, not only screen layout.','Reducing UX to visual styling or ease of use on one screen.'],
['User interview','', 'A structured conversation used to understand behavior and context.','Reconstruct the last monthly close.','Asking the participant to validate an idea.'],
['User story','', 'A format for expressing a user need or behavior in context.','As a manager, I need to detect margin variance.','Using the template without evidence.'],
['Value proposition','', 'A clear promise of value for a specific audience.','Close project profitability without consolidating spreadsheets.','Listing capabilities instead of value.'],
['Value risk','', 'The risk that a solution is not relevant or desirable enough.','Managers will not change their workflow.','Testing usability while ignoring importance.'],
['Viability risk','', 'The risk that a solution does not work for the business and its constraints.','Negative margin or a legal prohibition.','Reducing viability to pricing alone.'],
['Voice of Customer','VoC', 'A system for capturing and synthesizing customer signals.','Combine themes from tickets, calls, and interviews.','Counting requests as votes.'],
['Win/loss analysis','', 'A structured analysis of why commercial opportunities were won or lost.','Compare reasons by ICP and competitor.','Accepting the CRM reason without investigation.'],
['Wizard of Oz','', 'A test in which an apparently automated experience is operated manually behind the scenes.','A human curator produces recommendations shown as a workflow.','Hiding material risk or commitments from participants.'],
['Workaround','', 'An alternative method used to complete a job despite a limitation.','Export CSV and rebuild the report weekly.','Assuming every workaround deserves automation.'],
['Workflow','', 'The sequence of actions, decisions, information, and handoffs required to complete work.','Collect time, review exceptions, approve, and issue an invoice.','Using workflow as a synonym for one screen.']
];

const TERM_TRANSLATIONS = Object.fromEntries(GLOSSARY.map(entry => [entry[0], entry[2]]));

const TERM_DEEP_EXPLANATIONS = {
  'Ideal Customer Profile': 'An Ideal Customer Profile, usually shortened to ICP, describes the type of organization most likely to obtain substantial value from the product while creating a healthy relationship for the vendor. It is not a description of every current customer and it is not an individual persona. A useful ICP combines operational model, size, maturity, urgency, implementation ability, willingness to pay, and cost to serve. A profitability product might discover that its ICP is agencies with 20–100 people that bill by the hour and close margin weekly. The profile helps Product, Sales, and Marketing separate strategically relevant demand from requests coming from accounts unlikely to adopt, retain, or expand.',
  'Beachhead': 'Beachhead is a military metaphor for a small position established first so that broader expansion becomes possible. In product strategy, it means deliberately choosing a narrow initial segment with intense pain and favorable conditions for adoption before serving a broad market. A company might begin with agencies that bill by the hour, learn that workflow deeply, and build a strong position before expanding into consultancies or other professional-services firms. A beachhead is not the final market and is not simply the smallest available segment. It is selected because need, access, learning, defensibility, and expansion potential reinforce one another.',
  'Product Management': 'Product Management is the discipline of deciding which problems deserve investment, for whom they should be solved, and how a team will learn whether it created value. The work includes understanding customers, connecting opportunities to strategy, sequencing investments, exposing risks, coordinating delivery, and interpreting results. In a software company, Product Management might choose to reduce time to first value rather than add another capability requested by a few accounts. The discipline does not replace Design, Engineering, Sales, or leadership. It creates shared context and decision criteria so those specialties can work coherently together.',
  'Product Manager': 'A Product Manager improves the process by which product decisions are made. The title does not mean manager of engineers, sole author of the roadmap, or automatic representative of every customer opinion. A senior PM makes the problem, audience, evidence, impact, risks, alternatives, and trade-offs explicit, then helps the team choose and measure. Faced with low adoption, the PM does not immediately request a campaign. They separate eligible, exposed, attempted, activated, and retained users to determine whether the barrier is awareness, usability, or value. The central responsibility is the quality of judgment and learning even when execution is shared.',
  'Product thinking': 'Product thinking is a way of reasoning that begins with a problem and ends with a decision informed by results. It combines customer context, business goals, evidence, technical constraints, risk, and opportunity cost. A person demonstrates product thinking when a feature request leads them to ask who experiences the problem, how often, with what consequence, and which low-cost test can reduce the most important uncertainty. It does not depend on a title or on memorizing frameworks. Developers, Support professionals, founders, and operators can all practice it; formal product environments simply demand that the reasoning be organized and communicated explicitly.',
  'Opportunity cost': 'Opportunity cost is the value of the best alternative that cannot happen because another choice was made. Product capacity is limited, so a feature costs more than the hours required to build it. It also costs the learning, revenue, risk reduction, or experience improvement another initiative could have produced. Two weeks spent on an exclusive report may delay an onboarding correction affecting thousands of users. Because opportunity cost never appears on an invoice, organizations often ignore it. Naming it turns prioritization from a contest between ideas into a comparison between consequences.',
  'Guardrail metric': 'A guardrail metric protects the wider system from unacceptable damage while a primary metric is optimized. If a change raises conversion but also raises cancellations, complaints, or errors, the team should not declare victory by looking only at conversion. In shorter onboarding, activation may be primary while Support tickets and incorrect configurations act as guardrails. A useful guardrail has a defined population, threshold, and response before the test begins. Without a limit capable of pausing, changing, or reversing the intervention, it is merely another chart.',
  'Workflow': 'A workflow is the complete sequence of actions, decisions, information, and handoffs required to achieve a result. It exists beyond the product screens. To issue an invoice, a team may collect records, correct exceptions, obtain approval, create the document, and send it to a client. Mapping this sequence reveals participants, dependencies, waiting, risk, and workarounds that interface analysis alone would miss. When a customer requests a button, understanding the workflow shows whether the problem belongs in that action, an earlier decision, an approval rule, or missing information.',
  'SaaS': 'SaaS stands for Software as a Service. The product is provided continuously, usually over the internet, while the vendor remains responsible for availability, maintenance, security, updates, and Support. Recurring or usage-based billing is common, but subscription alone does not define SaaS. Customers can renew, expand, contract, or cancel, which makes activation, retention, churn, MRR, and NRR important. A financial tool used in a browser and paid monthly is SaaS; its success depends not only on the initial sale but also on recurring value and reliable operation.',
  'B2B': 'B2B stands for Business to Business, meaning that the commercial customer is an organization. People still use, buy, approve, and resist the product. In B2B, the user, buyer, economic buyer, champion, and stakeholder may all be different people, making discovery, adoption, and monetization more complex. In accounting software, analysts may use the product daily, a manager may champion it, Security may block it, and a director may approve the budget. B2B does not automatically mean enterprise; small companies and self-service purchases can also be B2B.'
};

const TERM_EXPLANATION_GROUPS = [
  {
    terms: new Set(['Activation','Adoption','Annual Recurring Revenue','Average Revenue per Account','Awareness','Baseline','Business impact','CAC','Churn','Cohort','Confidence','Conversion','Customer lifetime value','Engagement','Expansion revenue','Exposure','Funnel','Guardrail metric','Lagging indicator','Leading indicator','Minimum detectable effect','Monthly Recurring Revenue','Net Promoter Score','Net Revenue Retention','North Star Metric','Payback period','Reach','Retention','Revenue at risk','Support volume','Time to value']),
    explain: term => `Use ${term} only after naming the population, qualifying event, observation window, and data source. Those details determine whether two ${term} values are comparable and which action a change should trigger. A poorly defined ${term} may support a persuasive story while describing a different behavior from the one the team intended to improve.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Assumption','Customer advisory board','Customer journey','Discovery','Hypothesis','Jobs to be Done','Opportunity','Pattern validation','Premortem','Product analytics','Qualitative evidence','Quantitative evidence','Search logs','Segmentation','User interview','Voice of Customer','Win/loss analysis','Workaround']),
    explain: term => `${term} belongs to the work of reducing uncertainty before or after a product decision. Use ${term} with a stated question, a relevant audience, and evidence that could alter the recommendation. The value of ${term} is not the volume of notes or data collected; it is the clearer distinction it creates between an observed fact, an interpretation, and the next belief that still needs testing.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['A/B test','Beta','Concierge test','Design partner','Experiment','Fake door','Feature flag','Kill criteria','Limited rollout','Minimum viable product','Pilot','Post-launch review','Proof of concept','Prototype','Rollback','Rollback criteria','Rollout','Smoke test','Spike','Wizard of Oz']),
    explain: term => `${term} describes a particular way to learn or control exposure, not a universal stage every idea must pass through. Choose ${term} by identifying the uncertainty being reduced, the realism that evidence requires, the people exposed, and the exit condition. Evidence from ${term} is useful when it can cause a concrete decision such as continue, change, expand, pause, or stop.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Backlog','Commitment','Decision owner','Decision rule','Delivery','Dependency','Epic','Initiative','Instrumentation','Outcome','Output','Roadmap','Roadmap commitment','Scope','Scope reduction','User story']),
    explain: term => `${term} becomes useful when it clarifies the state, ownership, or boundary of work. Apply ${term} by making the intended outcome, responsible decision-maker, dependencies, confidence, and conditions for change visible. Used carelessly, ${term} can let an artifact for coordination silently become a promise, a strategy, or false evidence of customer value.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Feasibility risk','Product risk','Usability risk','Value risk','Viability risk','Reversibility']),
    explain: term => `${term} isolates a way in which an otherwise attractive bet can fail. Analysis of ${term} should name the assumption, the affected audience, the consequence of being wrong, and the evidence or safeguard needed before greater exposure. Collapsing ${term} into one generic risk makes teams test what is convenient instead of what is most capable of invalidating the decision.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Application Programming Interface','Artificial intelligence','Comma-Separated Values','Quality Assurance','Security','Single Sign-On']),
    explain: term => `${term} names a technical capability, practice, or constraint that affects the product experience and its operation. Discuss ${term} by connecting it to the user or business job, reliability and security expectations, implementation and maintenance cost, and the consequence of failure. Product judgment does not require implementing ${term}, but it does require understanding which decisions depend on it and involving the relevant specialists early.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Admin','Buyer','Buyer persona','Champion','Chief Financial Officer','Chief Operating Officer','Customer','Customer Success','Decision owner','Delivery Manager','Design','Detractor','Economic buyer','End user','Engineering','Founder','Persona','Power user','Product Manager','Project Manager','Prospect','Sales','Segment','Stakeholder','Support','Target segment','User']),
    explain: term => `${term} identifies a role, function, or audience whose goals, authority, incentives, and exposure may differ from others in the same account. When ${term} enters a product decision, clarify who performs the work, who receives value, who approves, who bears risk, and who can block or reverse the choice. Evidence associated with ${term} should not automatically be generalized to the whole customer.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Add-on','B2B','Core product','Customer Relationship Management','Enterprise','Freemium','Go-to-market','Ideal Customer Profile','Packaging','Paywall','Pipeline','PLG','Pricing','Product-led sales','Product-market fit','SaaS','Sales-led','Self-service','Serviceable Available Market','Serviceable Obtainable Market','Small and Medium-sized Business','Total addressable market','Trial','Value proposition']),
    explain: term => `${term} describes part of the commercial system connecting a chosen market to acquisition, value, purchase, retention, and expansion. Define ${term} with a specific audience, route to market, value exchange, and economic boundary. The same product can combine several motions, so ${term} should explain how this case works rather than substitute for analysis of buyers, users, costs, and behavior.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Beachhead','Cost of delay','Fit','Framework','Opportunity cost','Product','Product debt','Product Management','Product strategy','Product thinking','RICE','Strategic alignment','Sunk cost','Trade-off']),
    explain: term => `${term} helps frame a choice about direction, resources, or consequences. Use ${term} to state what the organization is trying to achieve, which alternatives are being compared, what will deliberately not happen, and which evidence supports the choice. ${term} earns its place only when it changes priorities or accepted losses; otherwise it is decoration around an unchanged opinion.`
  },
  {
    terms: new Set(['Feature','Feature request','Progressive disclosure','User Experience','Workflow']),
    explain: term => `${term} concerns how a need is represented or experienced in the product. Place ${term} inside the complete job, including triggers, information, decisions, handoffs, exceptions, and consequences beyond the interface. A wider view of ${term} helps the team avoid confusing a requested control or screen with the underlying problem and reveals whether a simpler rule, service, or process change could work better.`
  }
];

function termSlug(term) {
  return term.toLowerCase().normalize('NFD').replace(/[\u0300-\u036f]/g, '').replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, '-').replace(/^-|-$/g, '');
}

function termDisplay(entry) {
  return entry[1] ? `${entry[0]} · ${entry[1]}` : entry[0];
}

function termDetailedExplanation(entry) {
  if (TERM_DEEP_EXPLANATIONS[entry[0]]) return TERM_DEEP_EXPLANATIONS[entry[0]];
  const group = TERM_EXPLANATION_GROUPS.find(candidate => candidate.terms.has(entry[0]));
  const context = group
    ? group.explain(entry[0])
    : `${entry[0]} becomes useful when it separates this idea from neighboring concepts and turns it into a visible decision criterion. Name the object being analyzed, the relevant audience and context, the evidence available, and the consequence that could change the recommendation. That makes the vocabulary a tool for inspectable judgment rather than a sophisticated label.`;
  return `${entry[2]} ${context}`;
}

function termPopoverHtml(entry) {
  const slug = termSlug(entry[0]);
  return `<button class="term-popover-close" type="button" aria-label="Close explanation">Close</button><p class="term-kicker">Term introduced</p><h3 id="termPopoverTitle">${termDisplay(entry)}</h3><p class="term-literal"><strong>In plain English:</strong> ${TERM_TRANSLATIONS[entry[0]]}</p><p>${termDetailedExplanation(entry)}</p><p class="term-example"><strong>Concrete example:</strong> ${entry[3]}</p><p class="term-caution"><strong>Watch out:</strong> ${entry[4]}</p><a href="#term-${slug}">View the full glossary entry →</a>`;
}

function glossaryHtml() {
  return `<nav class="alphabet" aria-label="Alphabetical navigation">${[...new Set(GLOSSARY.map(x => x[0][0]))].map(letter => `<a href="#gloss-${letter}">${letter}</a>`).join('')}</nav><div class="glossary-list">${GLOSSARY.sort((a,b) => a[0].localeCompare(b[0], 'en')).map((x, i, arr) => { const letter = x[0][0].toUpperCase(); const newLetter = i === 0 || arr[i-1][0][0].toUpperCase() !== letter; return `${newLetter ? `<h3 id="gloss-${letter}" class="gloss-letter">${letter}</h3>` : ''}<article id="term-${termSlug(x[0])}" class="glossary-entry"><h4>${x[0]}${x[1] ? ` <span>${x[1]}</span>` : ''}</h4><p class="literal-translation"><strong>In plain English:</strong> ${TERM_TRANSLATIONS[x[0]]}</p><p>${termDetailedExplanation(x)}</p><p><strong>Example:</strong> ${x[3]}</p><p><strong>Common mistake:</strong> ${x[4]}</p></article>`; }).join('')}</div>`;
}

BOOK_PARTS.push({
  id: 'parte-7', title: 'Part VII — The final mental model', chapters: [
    { id: 'capitulo-26', number: 26, title: 'The complete Product Thinking system', content: `
      <p class="lead">The system is not an assembly line. It is a decision cycle in which each step creates a more precise question for the next, and results update the team’s understanding of the problem.</p>
      <div class="diagram final-map" aria-label="Complete Product Thinking map">${['Problem','User or segment','ICP and strategic fit','Evidence','Impact','Prioritization','Smallest test','Success metrics','Guardrails','Launch','Iterate, scale, or rollback'].map((x,i) => `<div class="node${i===0||i===10?' accent':''}">${x}</div>${i<10?'<div class="arrow">↓</div>':''}`).join('')}</div>
      <h3>How to move through the map</h3><p><strong>Problem</strong> begins with behavior and consequence. <strong>User or segment</strong> prevents empty averages. <strong>ICP and strategic fit</strong> ask whether the audience belongs to the chosen direction. <strong>Evidence</strong> separates signal from belief. <strong>Impact</strong> connects pain to value. <strong>Prioritization</strong> exposes what will be lost.</p>
      <p><strong>Smallest test</strong> buys learning before scale. <strong>Success metrics</strong> define the desired result. <strong>Guardrails</strong> limit damage. <strong>Launch</strong> includes instrumentation, rollout, and operation. <strong>Iterate, scale, or rollback</strong> converts the result into a decision. That decision may return to the original problem because the segment, mechanism, or evidence changed.</p>
      <h3>Discovery and Delivery as a continuous flow</h3><div class="diagram dual-track"><div class="track"><strong>Discovery</strong><span>problem → evidence → risks → test</span></div><div class="sync">↕ decisions and learning ↕</div><div class="track"><strong>Delivery</strong><span>scope → construction → rollout → operation</span></div></div>
      <p>The tracks are not departments. Engineering participates in feasibility during discovery; Product and Design observe behavior after delivery. A team can explore the next bet while stabilizing the previous one, but only when capacity and focus are real.</p>
      <aside class="callout error"><strong>Common mistake.</strong> Turning the map into a mandatory stage gate. Incidents, legal obligations, and reversible changes require different levels of evidence.</aside>
      <aside class="callout takeaway"><strong>Takeaway.</strong> Product thinking is the circuit connecting pain to a choice, a choice to a test, and a result to the next decision.</aside>` },
    { id: 'capitulo-27', number: 27, title: 'A checklist for product decisions', content: `
      <p class="lead">Use this page before a review, interview, or commitment. You do not need to check everything; you need to know why an item can safely be ignored.</p>
      <form class="decision-checklist"><fieldset><legend>Problem and audience</legend><label><input type="checkbox"> Can I describe the problem without naming a feature?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Do I have an observable episode, behavior, or consequence?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I separated user, buyer, customer, and stakeholder?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I defined the segment and its relationship to the ICP?</label></fieldset><fieldset><legend>Evidence and value</legend><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I separated fact, interpretation, hypothesis, and assumption?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I combined relevant qualitative and quantitative signals?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I sized user and business impact?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I stated confidence and what could change it?</label></fieldset><fieldset><legend>Choice</legend><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I compared alternatives, including doing nothing?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Are opportunity cost and cost of delay visible?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I considered total effort, dependencies, and reversibility?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I named the accepted trade-off and decision owner?</label></fieldset><fieldset><legend>Learning and delivery</legend><label><input type="checkbox"> Have I identified the risk most likely to kill the bet?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Is this the smallest test capable of reducing that risk?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Are success, leading, lagging, and guardrail measures defined?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Are instrumentation, rollout, and rollback planned?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Are iterate, scale, and kill conditions explicit?</label><label><input type="checkbox"> Is there an owner and date for the post-launch review?</label></fieldset></form>
      <aside class="callout takeaway"><strong>Pocket version.</strong> Problem, audience, evidence, impact, alternatives, cost, risk, test, metric, decision. If you can explain those ten elements in two minutes, the conversation is ready to deepen.</aside>` },
    { id: 'capitulo-28', number: 28, title: 'Essential glossary', content: `
      <p class="lead">This glossary is a translation into plain English, not a test of fluency. Every entry gives the professional term, a practical explanation, a concrete example, and the misuse most likely to make it unhelpful.</p>
      ${glossaryHtml()}
      <aside class="callout takeaway"><strong>Takeaway.</strong> Return to the glossary when a concept appears in conversation. Then create an example from your own work. Vocabulary sticks when it attaches to experience.</aside>` }
  ]
});
